<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / People: Bodies politic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nigel Whittaker, executive director of Kingfisher and chairman of the CBI's
distributive trades panel, is to switch retailing horses. After nearly seven
years on the CBI panel, he is now to take up the position of chairman of the
British Retail Consortium.
His replacement at the CBI is Alastair Eperon, director of corporate affairs
at Boots, and a previous chief executive of McAvoy Bayley, the public
relations firm.
Whittaker's new job as non-executive chairman is largely an honorary one.
However, it may have help to improve the BRC's links with the CBI's panel.
James May, the director general of the BRC, has admitted in public that he
remains distinctly unconvinced by the accuracy of the CBI distributive trade
survey. Whittaker, however, is - naturally enough - a great fan of the
survey he has presided over for the past seven years.
</TEXT>
