Nirex, he says, has not to date provided sufficiently convincing reasons to
override these policies.
The outcome of the government's review of the UK's nuclear industry,
including waste management policy, is still awaited, says Mr Cole, as is
further geological information from Nirex on the site.
Nirex, he says, has not provided information to convince the council there
are 'compelling reasons' for choosing the Sellafield site in preference to
alternatives.
A public inquiry - which would last two to three years - had not been
expected unless Nirex went ahead with a planning application for the
repository. All parties on the county council have been pressing the
government, so far without success, for a public inquiry into the RCF.
Nirex yesterday said it saw no strategic planning grounds for the refusing
or deferring approval on application which it described as purely a research
facility. Mr David Brown, Nirex's Cumbrian director, said: 'It cannot be
stressed too often that this is not a nuclear facility.'
