FT  15 DEC 94 / IBM sells 'surplus' plant to managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines has sold its manufacturing plant at Havant,
Hampshire, to its management in a deal worth about Pounds 50m.
The management group has formed a company, Xyratex, which has been running
the plant since the beginning of the month. It will continue to produce disk
drives, flexible circuits and networking equipment for IBM.
Last year IBM said the plant - one of the company's best-known European
facilities, which manufactures disk drives for personal and medium-range
computers - was one of three in Europe that was 'surplus to requirements'
because of industrial restructuring.
Two months ago it became known that IBM was planning to sell the plant and
that several manufacturing groups had invited to bid.
The management buy-out was led by Mr Ken Wilkie, former managing director,
and some 30 managers. Finance is being provided by Murray Johnstone, the
venture capital company. Senior debt has been provided by Midland Bank.
The plant employs more than 2,000 people and will have revenues of about
Pounds 300m a year.
It has recently signed contracts to make about 1m units a year of an
innovative drive design for JTS, a Californian company, and about 100,000
units a year for Nomai, a French removable drive company.
It will continue to develop recently launched lines of business in removable
data storage, test systems, network consultancy and applications software.
For example, it manufactures engine management systems for Aston Martin
sports cars and printing systems for music shops.
IBM has been cutting manufacturing capacity as it comes to terms with an
industry that has shifted to personal computers and networked systems rather
from mainframe computers.
Analysts question whether there is a future for disk drive manufacturing in
Europe when most electronics companies are transferring production to Asia
and the Pacific Rim. A contract awarded to Havant by Western Digital of the
US for 2m drives annually was cancelled earlier this year as a consequence
of changes in manufacturing strategy.
Mr Wilkie said yesterday he was confident that Havant's engineering
expertise and manufacturing prowess were a sufficient counter to Asia's
lower manufacturing costs. Computer makers, he said, were increasingly
looking for European sources of key components.
