FT  15 DEC 94 / Defence projects 'late and over cost'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
About 80 per cent of important defence equipment projects are running behind
schedule and there are 'large cost overruns' on a significant number of
projects, the Commons public accounts committee said yesterday.
The date by which the projects were due to be in-service had slipped by 32
months on average, according to a report from the cross-party committee of
MPs.
It added that the bill for the Eurofighter 2000 programme had spiralled to
slightly less than Pounds 1bn. The MPs warned that a cost overrun on any
project entailed cuts elsewhere in the programme.
They also expressed concern at a National Audit Office report which examined
five 'mid-life update projects' by which equipment is modernised. All five
missed deadlines or ran over budget. For example, the Tornado GR1 mid-life
update had slipped by five years and had a cost overrun of about 50 per
cent.
Delays to the updating of the Sea Harrier meant the modernised aircraft had
entered service only recently. The upgrade remedied deficiencies identified
during the Falklands War in 1982.
More than Pounds 500,000 has been spent on regimental swords, it was
disclosed yesterday: 560 new swords have been bought in the past five years
at a cost of Pounds 365,700, and 576 swords have been 'refurbished' at a
cost of Pounds 156,700.
