<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Charities to get tax plan exclusion
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday promised to alter the finance bill to exclude
charities and their subsidiaries from provisions announced in the Budget
aimed at closing a loophole used by some foreign companies with subsidiaries
in the UK.
Charities expressed their concern after the Budget that they appeared to be
caught by the provisions and could face big tax bills as a result of new
rules on 'thin capitalisation'.
Under the new rules UK subsidiaries would no longer be able to avoid
corporation tax by using profits to make interest payments. These have not
previously been taxable. The plan to tax such payments would affect UK
companies only where the company receiving the interest was not paying
corporation tax.
</TEXT>
<XX>
