<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Show of resistance disguises unity of business purpose: The
postal strike masked broad agreement between management and staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This week's Post Office dispute, which closed more than 100 main offices,
caused a predictable spat.
The UCW communication workers' union said that Monday's walkout, over
'backdoor privatisation' of main offices, was a tremendous success.
Management dismissed it as a flop.
One might conclude that the UCW, which campaigned so successfully to stop
the government's privatisation plans for the Post Office, was still at
daggers drawn with senior management, which had lobbied strenuously for a
sell-off.
However, appearances can be deceptive. Last month the UCW recommended that
its members accept a 2.8 per cent pay rise from November 1 to rise to 3.4
per cent from anuary 1.
Mr Alan Johnson, the union's general secretary, said that closure of main
offices and their transfer to franchised stores or supermarkets had been
happening since 1987. This week's walkout was merely an attempt to give the
issue a higher profile.
Although the counters side of the business employs about 9,000 UCW members,
the union stressed that 'this dispute does not epitomise our relationship
with the Post Office'.
But Mr Johnson said industrial relations were 'very tense' in the much
larger Royal Mail letters business, which employs 130,000 of his members.
The union is in the process of conducting about 40 strike ballots on local
disputes over hours and conditions.
The union said the Post Office's own attitude survey showed that employees'
morale was 'abysmal'. It said it would be pressing in forthcoming
negotiations for shorter working hours - and in particular for an end to
routine six-day working by most delivery staff.
Mr Johnson said: 'Seven-day working was stopped in 1849. So delivery staff
came into this century working on six days a week. We don't want them to go
into the next century still doing the same.'
Mr John Roberts, the Post Office's managing director of group services, took
a more relaxed view of the group's industrial relations. 'This is our
busiest time of year - disputes over overtime are almost traditional. Five
years ago we lost 5 per cent of man-days because of industrial action
between April and Christmas. Since April this year we have lost less than
0.1 per cent.'
However, Mr Roberts said: 'We had two-and-a-half years of total uncertainty
 -that certainly had an impact on morale. It is difficult to run a business
when you don't know which way you are heading.
'Now that it is clear we will remain in the public sector - at least for the
foreseeable future - we can focus on longer-term issues.'
Management is not unsympathetic to the UCW's complaint that low basic pay
means that postal workers rely too much on overtime to achieve reasonable
average pay. In the new year negotiations, the union will be seeking reduced
working hours, enhanced job security and a productivity scheme.
Mr Roberts said: 'Now is a very good time for us to take stock. We are going
to have a period of stability - we have got to make the most of that. There
is a lot of common ground on which to build.'
Mr Johnson is also anxious not to overstate the degree of industrial unrest,
and agrees with management that most of the present local disputes in Royal
Mail are likely to be settled without industrial action.
He said: 'We realise we're better off than in a lot of industries. We have a
fairly sophisticated industrial relations environment. While there might
have been some hawks passing through, most managers realise they need to
work with the unions.'
One goal that both the UCW and the management will press for is the
achieving of more commercial freedom for the Post Office, now that the
government has backed away from immediate privatisation.
There is some resentment on the union side that Mr Bill Cockburn, Post
Office chief executive, and Mr Michael Heron, chairman, both pressed so
vociferously for privatisation. Post Office leaders apparently felt they had
little choice, given the conditions with which the government seemed intent
on hedging the option of staying in the public sector.
Mr Roberts said: 'The issue for us was always commercial freedom - not
ownership. But the government said ownership within the public sector would
condemn us to slow decline. The key thing is that we must not let go of the
argument for commercial freedom.'
The union plans to launch a Postal Forum - to include consumer and industry
associations, charities and disability groups - in the new year to campaign
for greater commercial freedom.
Union and management will again press for a cut in this year's Pounds 226m
government levy on post service profits.
Mr Johnson said: 'We're dealing with the art of the possible - trying to
build a coalition. Our members are not naturally militant - we take the
brunt of any industrial action. Many of my members meet more members of the
public every day than senior management do all year.'
</TEXT>
