<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Clarke denies plan for more VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said yesterday that he did not intend to
use the lower 8 per cent value added tax rate - which now applies to
domestic fuel and power - to broaden the VAT base in the tax system.
'I have no intention of building on the lower rate,' he told the Commons
Treasury and civil service committee.
He said he did not choose to have the lower 8 per cent VAT rate - which was
forced on the government by last week's Commons defeat of its plans to lift
VAT on fuel to 17.5 per cent - and he did not plan to rush back into
broadening the VAT base. He had not, for example, considered levying VAT on
newspapers or magazines when preparing the Budget.
The chancellor also said:
He hoped that after the supply-side reforms of recent years, the economy
could sustain growth at a faster annual rate than 2 per cent to 2.5 per cent
without risking inflation.
He had acted promptly last week to plug the hole in his Budget caused by the
VAT revolt because it was dangerous for a nation to borrow heavily in
financial markets.
Political considerations had reinforced his decision last week to raise base
rates to 6.25 per cent from 5.75 per cent. However, the rate rise had been
justified on economic grounds.
Mr Clarke stressed that he was pleased with the present monetary regime in
which there was more openness over policy and the governor of the Bank of
England played a more prominent role than previously. But in a cryptic
remark, he hinted that the rate rise might be reversible if conditions
warranted it. It was 'possibly one of the few reversible decisions I have
taken', he said.
Mr Clarke was upbeat about the economy. Britain as an industrial nation was
'now quite spectacularly good' compared with 15 years ago.
He cited Mr Jacques Delors, the outgoing president of the European
Commission, as having said that the UK would be one of only three EU
countries to meet the economic convergence criteria of the Maastricht Treaty
in 1996. The UK would meet them easily, while Germany would need 'good luck
and a following wind'.
This meant that Britain was on course for the 'ideal situation' of being
able to decide if it wanted to enter the third and final stage of economic
and monetary union with a single currency and European central bank. His
main aim was to keep Emu as a 'genuinely open option' for the UK.
He was less forthcoming about future tax policy and refused to name the
conditions under which he would or would not cut taxes in a future Budget.
He admitted that taxes could not be cut when the public finances were
unhealthy but said that chancellors had to look at 'the overall situation'
when making decisions on fiscal policy.
</TEXT>
