<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Post Office triples its profits for half year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office yesterday reported half-yearly pre-tax profits up more than
threefold on last year, and announced that there would be no early increase
in stamp prices.
In spite of uncertainty about the future status of the industry, Post Office
pre-tax profits rose to Pounds 198m in the six months to September 25, from
Pounds 59m for the same period last year.
This puts the Post Office on course to meet its government levy of Pounds
226m, taken from its post-tax profits for the full year 1994-95, without a
stamp price rise. However, Mr Michael Heron, chairman, refused to rule out a
price rise for the whole of 1995.
Mr Heron continued to insist that decline was in prospect unless the
government gives the Post Office greater commercial freedom to run the Royal
Mail, the letter delivery division which accounts for most of the industry's
turnover and profits.
The government last month backed away from its plan to privatise the Post
Office, fearing that the steadfast opposition of about 10 Tory MPs would
lead to defeat in the Commons.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, has yet to decide the
future status of the industry within the public sector. The Post Office
board is anxious that its healthy financial performance does not reinforce
the case for the status quo, yet the Treasury appears intent on resisting
moves to reduce the government profits levy and other commercial
constraints.
The half-yearly results showed a rise of 1m in the number of letters
delivered a day by the Royal Mail over the past year, taking the figure to
64m. The division's turnover increased from Pounds 1.96bn to Pounds 2.15bn
and its pre-tax profit from Pounds 55m to Pounds 199m.
The counters division, which has responsibility for high street and village
post offices, also reported a sharp increase in profit, from Pounds 10m to
Pounds 14m.
Overall productivity continued to improve, with employee numbers down by
1,500 to 191,200 over the year to September.
However, Parcelforce, the Post Office's parcel delivery division, went
deeper into the red, reporting pre-tax losses up from Pounds 17m to Pounds
28m.
Mr Bill Cockburn, chief executive, blamed Parcelforce's problems on the
intensity of competition in the parcels market, where the Post Office
competes with more than 400 private companies.
The Post Office told the government it needed to invest Pounds 400m this
year to modernise its plant, but was allowed only Pounds 320m.
Referring to the increase in the government levy on the Post Office, from
Pounds 66m two years ago to Pounds 226m this year, Mr Heron said: 'The
government should be ashamed of taking this level of profit out without
allowing us the necessary investment for the future.'
</TEXT>
