<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Charities to get tax plan exclusion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday promised to alter the finance bill to exclude
charities and their subsidiaries from provisions announced in the Budget to
close a loophole used by some foreign companies with subsidiaries in the UK,
Jim Kelly writes.
Charities expressed their concern after the Budget that they appeared to be
caught by the provisions and could face big tax bills as a result of new
rules on 'thin capitalisation'.
Under the new rules UK subsidiaries would no longer be able to avoid
corporation tax by using profits to make interest payments. These have not
previously been taxable. The plan to tax such payments would affect UK
companies only where the company receiving the interest was not paying
corporation tax.
Sir George Young, financial secretary to the Treasury, in a reply to a
written parliamentary question, said: 'The thin capitalisation proposals
were not intended to have an adverse effect on the voluntary sector.
'It is now apparent that, in some cases, they could do so. I therefore
intend amending the provision at the committee stage of the finance bill to
exclude charities and their subsidiaries from its scope.'
</TEXT>
