<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Anonymity for lottery winners thrown into uncertainty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's High Court ruling that the Pounds 17.9m winner of the National
Lottery can be named has cast a cloud over the ability of Camelot, the
National Lottery operator, to protect the identity of jackpot winners who
wish to remain anonymous.
The ruling, by Sir John Wood, came just 24 hours after another High Court
judge imposed the gagging order on the press. It confounded some media
lawyers who had been predicting earlier in the day that the temporary
injunction was likely to be made permanent next week.
At a brief private hearing on Tuesday evening, at which the newspapers were
not present, Camelot is believed to have argued that publication of the
winner's name against his wishes would have amounted to a breach of
confidence.
Under the rules set by the National Lottery regulator, the identity of a
lottery winner is treated as confidential information. Camelot is prevented
from revealing any personal details about a winner unless it has that
person's prior written consent.
Courts have shown in the past that they are prepared to stop newspapers from
disclosing confidential information where it has been obtained in
circumstances such that the press knew it was confidential or private.
Lawyers said both the Sun and Daily Mirror knew the winner had requested
anonymity and therefore that his identity was confidential information
between him and Camelot.
In deciding whether to grant the injunction the judge had to weigh the
public interest in upholding the right to protect private information
against the public interest in knowing his identity.
The judge on Tuesday was persuaded that Camelot at least had an arguable
case and should be granted the ban. But at a two-hour private hearing
yesterday, Sir John Wood decided there was no legal basis for granting an
injunction.
Publication of details about the winner's job, family and the fact that he
lived in the north of England meant his identity was already 'substantially
in the public domain', the judge said. There was therefore no point in
continuing the ban.
Had the injunction been upheld the newspapers would have faced heavy fines
and the possible imprisonment of their editors for contempt of court if they
had decided to go ahead and publish the winner's name.
Now that the injunction has been lifted they are free to identify him. But
in view of the fact that they had already indicated before Camelot obtained
the gagging order that they would respect the winner's request for
anonymity, the judge ordered the National Lottery operator to pay the
newspapers' costs of challenging the ban. These are estimated at Pounds
5,000.
Camelot has indicated that it will not appeal. Lawyers said last night that
if the court ruling was allowed to stand it must cast doubt on the lottery
operator's ability to protect the privacy of winners who request anonymity
as it is required to do under the terms of its licence.
The court's decision also appeared to be a slap in the face for the lottery
regulator, Mr Peter Davis, who last night acknowledged he had no powers to
prevent members of the public or the media revealing a winner's identity.
He said he had no evidence that Camelot had breached the terms of its
licence but in view of allegations made against the company, he would be
carrying out an investigation of its handling of the affair.
</TEXT>
