<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / DIY chain faces kitchen refunds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The collapse of an insurance company has left Texas Homecare, the DIY
retailer owned by Ladbroke group, facing the possibility of having to hand
money back to customers who bought kitchens from it in 1992.
To boost the sale of kitchens during the recession, Texas launched a
promotion promising customers their money back in 10 years' time if they
bought Wrighton kitchens worth up to Pounds 1,500.
A percentage of the retail price was invested in a trust fund in Jersey to
provide funds for customers who remembered to claim their money back in
2002.
However, Texas had insured itself against the possibility of claims
exceeding the proceeds of the trust fund with MGI, an insurance company
which recently failed.
Texas is now taking legal action against the trust fund - run by the Royal
Bank of Canada group - and brokers who advised it on which company to insure
with. It wants them to shoulder the cost of any excess claims at the end of
the 10-year period.
Texas said yesterday: 'The trust fund was based on a calculation by
actuaries of the number of people likely to come back in 2002 and ask for
their money back. But the insurance against excess claims turns out to have
been placed with a lesser-rated insurance company.'
The DIY retailer could not provide figures for the number of customers who
had taken up the special offer - although the then chairman Mr Ron Trenter
said at the time that kitchen sales had tripled. Texas said yesterday the
amount of money involved was 'not material as far as the company is
concerned'.
It said the offer, a promotional method which originated in the US, had run
for only a few months in 1992, and this was the only time Texas had used
this method.
It added: 'This was effectively just another deep discount offer.'
</TEXT>
