<DOCNO>FT944-3080</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ELOCSABTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Aircraft project decision criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A government decision not to support the European Future Large Aircraft
project could allow Germany to overtake the UK as the world leader in
wing-design technology, says a study published yesterday.
The project is the rival to the US Hercules C130J as the replacement for the
RAF's Hercules transport fleet.
The academic study, commissioned by the Western Development Partnership, an
economic regeneration agency based in Avon, examined the significance of
British Aerospace's 20 per cent stake in the European Airbus consortium.
It said the UK government's failure to take up the 37.5 per cent stake
originally on offer would, by 2010, have cost the country Pounds 18bn of
business and thousands of jobs.
BAe's design team, the study said, faced a wait of six years before the next
generation of Airbus required major wing development. The FLA design would
fill that gap and provide substantial work for other UK companies.
</TEXT>
