<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / European energy law accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers from at least 45 countries plus a European Union representative
will meet in Lisbon over the weekend to sign the European Energy Charter,
which aims to establish a legal agreement for investment and trade in energy
between western organisations and those in central and eastern Europe. The
charter was originally proposed after the fall of communism to provide the
west with a vehicle for supporting Russian and east European industry.
However, its completion has been delayed by disputes over the legal
requirements that should be set and the pace of Russian reform. The US will
delay signing the charter until next year, while Norway's vote to stay out
of the EU casts doubt on its signature. Russia has said it will sign in
principle, but it is unclear whether they will do so as early as this
weekend.
</TEXT>
