<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 94 / Nato to study boosting UN mission in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Britain reacted coolly yesterday to French proposals for reinforcing the UN
mission in Bosnia, saying military experts would have to decide what was
feasible.
However, military commanders from the nine Nato members which contribute
troops to Bosnia, plus the US and Italy, will meet in the Netherlands next
week to consider ways of strengthening the UN's hard-pressed humanitarian
and peacekeeping mission.
The French suggestions - which include securing Sarajevo airport and
creating a secure route from the Bosnian capital to the Adriatic - would
serve the twin purpose of reinforcing the UN while it remains in Bosnia and
making a withdrawal easier.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, UK defence secretary, said he could not comment on the
practicability of the French ideas until they had been examined by military
experts. He stressed that there could be no question of altering the UN's
mandate.
Yesterday's meeting of Nato defence ministers grouped the US, Canada and 13
of its European allies but not France, which has opted out of the alliance's
military wing. The meeting focused strongly on refining contingency plans
for a possible UN withdrawal from Bosnia, although diplomats stressed a
pullout was not desirable or imminent.
As sketched out in a blueprint drawn up by Nato military planners, a
withdrawal of UN forces from Bosnia would be much the most ambitious
military operation in which the alliance has been involved. Planners
estimate that up to 45,000 troops would be required, of which 25,000 would
be earmarked for combat roles, plus 70 combat aircraft, 80 tanks and 180
helicopters.
Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, yesterday reaffirmed Washington
would provide up to half the combat troops, with conditions:
command of any withdrawal operations would have to be transferred
unconditionally from the UN to Nato;
the total force would have to be large enough to intimidate any hostile
party; and
the US Congress would have to approve.
US officials said they hoped a new UN posture would be worked out and
approved by the end of next week.
</TEXT>
