<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / International Capital Markets: OTC outstandings may top
Dollars 30,000bn - Derivative Instruments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The total value of outstandings in the over-the-counter derivatives market
seems likely to exceed Dollars 30,000bn by the end of this year, according
to Swaps Monitor, the specialist New York-based publication.
The projections - based on limited information currently available - imply
growth this year of at least 20 per cent.
Swaps Monitor estimates that the global market in interest rates swaps - one
of the most popular derivatives contracts - will be more than Dollars
12,000bn compared with Dollars 8,200bn in 1993.
The 1994 projections are contained in the publication's annual review of the
derivatives industry*, which consists of a comprehensive breakdown of
figures for 1993.
The survey shows that the outstanding value of OTC contracts increased by 20
per cent last year to reach Dollars 25,500bn. Foreign exchange forward
contracts - the biggest single class of business - increased to Dollars
9,500bn from Dollars 8,400bn.
The outstanding value of forward rate agreements and interest rate options
also rose, to Dollars 3,500bn from Dollars 3,300bn and to Dollars 2,000bn
from Dollars 1,200bn, respectively.
The survey also indicates that there is a high degree of concentration in
the OTC market with a few large players controlling large chunks of
business.
* The World's Major Derivatives Dealers: Swaps Monitor Publications, Inc 648
Broadway, suite 705, New York, NY 10012 Telephone (212) 254 9500
</TEXT>
