<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Australia raises rates to 7.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Official interest rates in Australia were raised by a full one percentage
point to 7.5 per cent early today, the third upward adjustment since August.
The Reserve Bank of Australia made its move at 9.30 am local time, as
markets opened.
The action was widely expected a week ago, following the regular meeting of
the RBA board, and acknowledgments by both Mr Bernie Fraser, the RBA
governor, and Mr Ralph Willis, the nation's treasurer, that the surge in the
Australian economy needed to be moderated before it threatened the country's
inflation rate. Economists, puzzled by last week's inaction, welcomed
today's move, but suggested that a further increase might still be necessary
in the first quarter of 1995.
Figures published two weeks ago showed that the Australian economy grew by a
rate of 6.4 per cent, year-on-year, in the September quarter, and by 7.3 per
cent if the drought-depressed farm sector was excluded. This is the fastest
rate posted by any OECD country in the current global recovery.
Most economists believe that growth rates in excess of five per cent will be
destabilising in the medium-term, although the nation's inflation rate
remains under 2 per cent at present.
Ahead of today's move, the RBA had already lifted official interest rates by
a total of 175 basis points over the past four months - the first move
coming in August and the second, in late-October.
Mr Willis said today's rate rise reflected the government and Reserve Bank's
commitment 'to maintain a low inflation environment and encourage further
significant and sustained reductions in unemployment'. The government has
also hinted recently that it may use fiscal means to depress demand. Earlier
this week, in Sydney, Mr Willis indicated that higher taxes might be
considered as part of the mid-year review in January, although he gave no
hints about the type of changes which might result.
</TEXT>
