<DATE>941214
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / London Stock Exchange: Rec speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bid speculation enlivened the regional electricity companies (recs) sector
as rumours that a takeover offer for Northern Electricity is imminent did
the rounds. The stock climbed 23 to 910p on 3.1m turnover.
The new speculation centred on international trading group Jardine Matheson,
with the talk suggesting it would be a way for the group to move funds out
of Hong Kong and into the UK. However, a bid from Scottish Power or Hanson,
both mentioned last week as possible predators, was not ruled out by some
observers.
Further buying of the stock was encouraged by a clutch of broker
recommendations. NatWest Securities advised clients to buy Northern but
warned: 'There is a possibility of corporate activity in the sector and
Northern looks as likely a target as any. However, with the (sale of the
National) Grid details not yet known, we believe the timing is wrong.'
Smith New Court recommended the recs as a whole, and Mr Kevin Lapwood at the
brokerage said: 'On fundamentals these stocks are cheap.' Scottish Power
hardened 1 1/2 to 331 1/2 p.
Interest rate concern appeared to spread rapidly across the building
materials sector, making deep inroads into a number of shares and leading to
heavy volumes.
Tarmac traded 12m shares, including a single deal of 4.7m, Caradon saw 3.3m
turnover, while plumbing specialist Spring Ram, boosted by the sale of a
block of family trust shares, soared to 30m trades.
Rugby was the stock most troubled by the industry's fears for an interest
rate led slide in demand, tumbling more than 5 per cent, with the shares
down 6 at 105p in 2.7m turnover. Blue Circle fell 6 to 274p on 2m traded,
RMC retreated 21 to 969p and Tarmac ended a penny adrift at 113 1/2 p.
Caradon finished 2 lower at 228p.
Behind the Spring Ram volume was a big deal by BZW, which sold 15m shares,
or 3.3 per cent of the group's equity, on behalf of the family trust of Mr
Bill Rooney, former Spring Ram chairman.
Favourable press comment and a general feeling that the recent concerns over
Christmas trading had been overdone boosted several of the leading retail
stocks. Marks &amp; Spencer rose 5 1/2 to 375p, but renewed doubts about the
trading picture at Kingfisher saw the shares relinquish an early lead of 10
to end just 2 up at 422p.
Bid excitement in the merchant banking sector faded slightly yesterday as
profit-taking saw all the major candidates retreat. SG Warburg, under the
scrutiny of Morgan Stanley, slipped 9 to 784p, while its 75 per cent-owned
fund management arm Mercury Asset Management dropped 32 to 718p.
Oil majors Shell and BP were firm ahead of BP's showpiece annual
presentation today and talk that one leading US broker had been recommending
the stock. Dealers cited CJ Lawrence, but veteran analyst Mr Charles Maxwell
said that with crude prices still under pressure it was premature to expect
a rally.
Paper group David S. Smith surprised the market with figures well above
forecasts but the shares barely moved. It appeared that an earlier sell
recommendation from one house had led to a line of 1.6m shares being placed
and not finding a home.
Consequently, interims of Pounds 40.4m, against Pounds 13.7m last time, and
a very upbeat trading statement saw the shares firm only a penny to 499p.
Nevertheless, analysts were upgrading forecasts, with a confident James
Capel boosting its prediction by Pounds 23m to Pounds 95m, believed to be
the top end of the range.
Elsewhere in the sector, James Capel turned seller on Arjo Wiggins Appleton,
cutting by Pounds 20m its figures for 1995 and 1996 to Pounds 260m and
Pounds 310m respectively. The house made the move to reflect the squeeze on
margins in the US. Arjo slipped 4 1/2 to 246 1/2 p.
Pharmaceuticals group SmithKline Beecham moved ahead strongly as some of the
company's supporters stressed their enthusiasm following a positive global
conference on Monday.
Smith New Court reiterated its positive stance and edged up some of its long
term forecasts, analyst Mr Paul Woodhouse arguing that if the stock were to
return to an acceptable rating, then it had a 20 per cent upside from
current levels. The 'A' shares appreciated 11 to 434 1/2 p, with combined
turnover in the 'A' stock and Units hitting 11.6m.
Chemicals group BOC fell 9 to 707p in reaction to a sell recommendation from
Credit Lyonnais Laing. Meanwhile, BTP held steady at 285p, with Hoare Govett
presenting it as a buying opportunity.
Vague bid speculation was heard elsewhere in the recs. Talk that Southern
Electricity, which reported bumper interim figures, may be thinking of a
takeover offer for a water company in a neighbouring area checked a further
advance in its shares. They closed 6 up at 756p. In addition, Seeboard and
South West Electricity were mentioned as possible targets. The former jumped
21 to 421p, while the latter climbed 31 to 788p.
Transport group NFC moved ahead strongly in 5m volume on the announcement
that a board member was a big, personal buyer of the shares. Sir Christopher
Bland, who takes up the post of chairman next month, has purchased 500,000
shares at 146 1/2 p. The news pushed NFC up 6 to 153p.
Diversified industrial groups BTR and Hanson were again two of the most
active Footsie stocks, with a combined 19.4m shares traded as talk of
switching out of Hanson persisted. Hanson closed fractionally lower at 227
1/2 p after 10m turnover, while BTR shed 1 1/2 to 277p.
</TEXT>
