<PROFILE>_AN-ELNEAAGKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941214
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / London Stock Exchange: Early rise in shares eroded by sell
programme - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sizeable sell programme executed in mid-morning put paid to any chances of
the UK equity market maintaining an early strong rally.
Also affecting sentiment was another disappointing performance by the gilts
market ahead of this morning's crucial economic data, which sees the
publication of inflation figures for November, monthly unemployment details,
news of underlying average earnings for October and unit wage costs for the
latest three months.
There was no real pressure, however, from across the Atlantic, where Wall
Street was never anything but steady and marginally higher on balance well
after London closed. Strategists said US markets had given a steadfast
response to the day's economic news, which showed a surprisingly good core
rise in producer prices but worryingly high retail sales that were well
above consensus forecasts.
The FT-SE 100 Index, which had fallen more than 2 per cent over the previous
two sessions, managed to end the day 3.0 up at 2,946.4. The FT-SE Mid 250
Index never looked like matching the FT-SE 100's early performance and
eventually settled 0.8 firmer at 3,373.2.
Dealers said the market had also been restrained by various technical
factors affecting markets across the globe. The FT-SE future December
contract expires on Friday, as does a series of German derivatives
instruments. Friday also brings 'triple witching hour' in the US, where all
the major derivatives contracts expire. Such expiries are often the trigger
for exaggerated movements in international stock markets.
The Footsie kicked off yesterday morning in good shape, opening almost 20
points better at 2,946.4, thanks mainly to a solid overnight performance
from Wall Street, where the Dow index continued to confound the pundits by
closing some 27 points higher.
But there was little institutional business in London and prices quickly
began to trickle back, influenced also by a retreat by some European equity
markets, notably Germany, which was hit by a Morgan Stanley downgrade.
In mid-morning the full force of a sizeable sell programme saw early gains
entirely wiped out and the FT-SE 100 Index fell into negative territory,
eventually hitting a session's low of 2,938.8, down a net 4.6.
Thereafter, share prices embarked on a slow recovery, moving back to
positive territory after Wall Street delivered a reassuring opening.
The latest Confederation of British Industry survey of distributive trades,
although pointing to a continued slowdown in sales, failed to cause any
damage in the retailing sectors, which have underperformed the market by a
considerable amount this year. The stores sector provided two of the FT-SE
100's best performers on the day in Boots and Marks and Spencer.
Marketmakers mostly remained unconvinced with the market's performance and
were noticeably wary of Wall Street. 'I am still sure we will see Wall
Street upsetting the applecart,' said one senior dealer. He added that the
London market had been 'blown around in a light breeze' and fund managers
remained unconvinced about short term opportunities.
He did not rule out, however, the chances of a rerun of the big gains in the
market between Christmas and the new year when derivatives activity, mostly
featuring tailor-made OTC trades, reaches a peak.
Regional electricity stocks provided some of the sharpest action in the
market, with Southern Electricity continuing the long list of 20 per
cent-plus interim dividend increases and the takeover speculation in
Northern Electricity continuing to build.
Turnover in equities reached a healthy 685.7m shares, with activity in
non-Footsie stocks accounting for over half the total. Customer business on
Monday was worth Pounds 1.4bn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
