FT  14 DEC 94 / International Company News: US airline wins further reprieve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Trans World Airlines, the US carrier struggling to avoid a liquidity crisis,
said two aircraft lessors had agreed to defer payments which were due in
November, allowing the airline to save Dollars 15m in cash and keep four
Boeing 767-200 aircraft in its fleet.
It also said an informal committee of preferred stockholders had agreed a
proposal for the company's financial restructuring, under which they would
get three times more equity in the company than holders of the common stock.
In October, TWA announced a plan under which creditors were asked to swap
Dollars 800m of the company's Dollars 1.8bn of debt for new equity.
