<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / International Company News: Union Miniere delays share issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union Miniere, the Belgian metals group, yesterday postponed the flotation
of its Swedish subsidiary, Ammeberg Mining, because it failed to achieve the
pricing it wanted. The delay again highlights the weak state of the new
issues market.
'The mine is not part of our core business, but it is a valuable asset and
we are not prepared to sell at a give-away price,' UM said.
However, bankers associated with the issue said the flotation would have had
problems at any price because international investment institutions were
tired and nervous after a difficult year. 'They are just not interested.
They want to start afresh in January,' said one.
Apart from a general malaise in the new issues market, the Ammeberg
flotation also suffered because of what Mr Nick Hatch, analyst at Ord
Minnett, an associate of Jardine Fleming, describes as 'indigestion' in the
resources sector. He calculates that resource companies so far this year
have raised Dollars 8.7bn and, by the year-end, the total will be nearly
twice the Dollars 5bn raised in 1993.
Other recent resource casualties include Samax, the UK company with African
mining interests which shelved a Pounds 16m flotation two weeks ago, and
Alumax, the US aluminium group, which postponed indefinitely the issue of 8m
new shares worth about Dollars 250m. Kymmene, Finland's second largest
forestry group, last week unexpectedly called off plans to raise more than
FM1.5bn (Dollars 307m) in a domestic and overseas share issue.
Two other resources companies are touring institutions in the hope of
raising money before the year-end: Banesto, the Spanish bank, wants to sell
39 per cent of Asturiana de Zinc, which owns the largest zinc smelter in the
world; while Stillwater Mining of the US, the only primary platinum group
metals producer outside South Africa, is looking for about Dollars 70m.
UM planned an initial public offering of nearly 11m Ammeberg shares, or 95
per cent of the company, at between SKr112 and SKr130 each. This valued
Ammeberg at between SKr1.26bn and SKr1.46bn (Dollars 167.3m and Dollars
193.9m).
Ammeberg, which was to be quoted on the Stockholm stock exchange, operates
the Zinkgruvan zinc-lead-silver underground mine in south-central Sweden,
which produces about 10 per cent of the western world's zinc.
UM said last year it wanted to give up its role as the world's biggest zinc
producer. It has closed its zinc refining plant at Overpelt in Belgium and
cancelled plans to double capacity at its Balen zinc refinery, also in
Belgium.
In February, UM sold its Union Zinc subsidiary in the US to Savage
Resources, a small Australian company, for USDollars 200m. Flotation of the
Swedish zinc subsidiary would have rounded off the rationalisation process.
</TEXT>
