<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Greenalls 10% ahead to Pounds 74.8m - First
full-year contribution from Devenish helps advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first full-year contribution from the Devenish pub chain helped
Greenalls Group report a 10 per cent rise in pre-tax profits from Pounds 68m
to Pounds 74.8m for the year to September 30.
The smooth integration of Devenish should continue to bring benefits this
year, which was off to a good start for the whole group, Mr Andrew Thomas,
chairman, said.
The group should also benefit from new supply agreements with brewers,
improving hotel returns, new concepts in its off-licence chain and expansion
of Tavern, its drinks wholesaling business.
The Devenish pubs, acquired for Pounds 214m in July 1993, contributed
operating profits of Pounds 24.5m and were earnings enhancing.
Pre-tax profits were struck after exceptional costs of Pounds 13.4m (profits
of Pounds 165,000), incurred mostly in closing Greenalls' soft drink maker.
Before exceptionals, profits rose 30 per cent and benefited from an extra
week of trading in the latest year.
The group's pubs operating profits were up 39 per cent at Pounds 75.9m, or
up 8 per cent without Devenish. Food sales per outlet rose 9 per cent and
drink sales 5 per cent. Premier House restaurants and lodges raised profits
by 57 per cent to Pounds 16.4m, or by 35 per cent without Devenish.
De Vere Hotels benefited from rising room and occupancy rates which helped
it to an 18 per cent rise in profits to Pounds 19.8m. Revenue per available
room was up 7 per cent to Pounds 32. The group's six US hotels, which are
for sale, turned in Pounds 768,000 (Pounds 145,000).
Off-licence profits slipped 4.7 per cent to Pounds 4.3m, but new management
and trading concepts brought a second half recovery after an 11 per cent
drop in first half profits. Drinks manufacture and distribution and leisure
contributed Pounds 8.4m, up 33 per cent.
A net cash outflow of Pounds 25.8m in the latest year should fall to an
outflow of between Pounds 5m and Pounds 10m this year as hotel building
ended, the company said. Borrowing rose to Pounds 395m (Pounds 368.5m) for
gearing of 55 per cent (46 per cent).
A proposed final dividend of 7.77p makes 13.1p for the year, up 6 per cent.
Earnings per share were 26.09p (28.37p) fully diluted after exceptionals and
30.78p (28.28p) before. Turnover from continuing operations rose 23 per cent
to Pounds 716.2m.
COMMENT
Highly advantageous long-term supply agreements with brewers show the value
to Greenalls of quitting brewing to concentrate on retailing. Only
Boddington Group offers a similar play in a fair-sized company. But
Greenalls has a better geographic spread and is more innovative. Steady
growth in pubs and a rising contribution from new hotels should help pre-tax
profits hit Pounds 97.5m this year for earnings of 34.5p. This puts the
shares on a realistic multiple of 12.3 on yesterday close of 425p, up 9p.
</TEXT>
