<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Global equity buyers dance to a Latin beat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last year the global equity market was blown up like a bubble but in 1994 it
has behaved more like a sponge. The eager US pension funds and mutual fund
investors have seen the FT-Actuaries World Index mostly reverse in the
second half-year the 3 per cent gain of the first six months.
This is the relatively benign picture as viewed from the perspective of a
dollar-based investor. The Swiss fund manager, however, thinks the world
index is down by 13 per cent, the Japanese by 8 per cent.
The spread around an unexciting global average performance has been less
dispersed than in 1993. The key features have been relative strength in
Japan, up 16 per cent in terms of dollars, and in parts of Latin America,
where Brazil - newly admitted to the World Index list - is up more than 60
per cent.
Weakness has been concentrated in Asia, focused on Malaysia and, especially,
Hong Kong where the index fall has been 37 per cent. There has been more
modest relative weakness in some of the European stock markets, notably
those of France and the UK. By the close last night London's Footsie Index
was showing a decline of 14 per cent on the year.
These movements clearly reflect the flows of funds across borders, in so far
as slow and patchy statistics permit them to be tracked. The notable event
in 1994 has been the rush of Dollars 47bn (Pounds 28.6bn) of foreign funds
into Japanese equities in the first half. But the benefit was seen in the
currency as much as in the stock market, where overstretched Japanese
financial institutions have taken advantage of the gaijin money to improve
their balance sheets.
There were better rewards from the cascade of dollars into South America. In
the first half, US investors put Dollars 5.2bn into Latin America but only
Dollars 600m into Asia (excluding Japan). In fact money was withdrawn from
Hong Kong in the first quarter, and despite a flow back during the early
summer the outflow appears to have been resumed more recently.
The challenge for the global investor is how to front-run these ebbs and
flows of hot money, mostly deriving from the US. UK fund managers used to be
among the leading global players but have recently been sitting largely on
the sidelines - where their performance has suffered.
Thus UK pension funds began the year with less than half the World Index
weightings in Japan and the US, and two or three times the weightings in
Asia (excluding Japan) and continental Europe. The money was in all the
wrong places.
During the year there has been some modest shifting of money into Japan and
more recently a repatriation from continental Europe. But according to
measurement data from the WM Company, the median overseas equity portfolio
of a UK pension fund was showing a negative return of 3.3 per cent by the
end of the third quarter, suggesting nine-month underperformance against the
World ex-UK Index of some 5 per cent. Of course, this has to be seen in the
context of outperformance of a massive 14 per cent in 1993.
Recently the UK fund managers' own domestic market appears to have been
under attack by foreign sellers. Can this be the start of the much-feared
sell-off by US international mutual funds as their cash inflows turn
negative?
As it happens, international investors have themselves taken a dim view
recently of the US stock market - which still accounts for 33 per cent of
global market capitalisation. Foreigners were net sellers of Dollars 2bn of
US equities in the second quarter. But this was a fleabite and Wall Street
has remained amazingly steady, despite pressures from the bond bear market.
Flow of funds statistics are so out of date that we can only guess at the
most recent trends. The modest recovery of the dollar would certainly argue
that some repatriation of funds has been proceeding. The danger is that by
imposing currency losses on remaining US global portfolios the effect will
be destabilising.
Until Americans have a longer track record as major cross-border portfolio
investors their behaviour will continue to worry and perplex the established
global players.
</TEXT>
<XX>
