<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Chechnya action leads to rift in Russian military
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LEVINE and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GROZNY, VLADIKAVKAZ
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A rift among Russian top brass emerged yesterday as senior military
officials criticised the government's effort to subdue the breakaway Chechen
republic.
General Alexander Lebed and General Boris Gromov, who commanded Soviet
forces during the Afghan war, warned that the intervention in Chechnya might
lead to a bloody and drawn-out guerrilla war.
'Step by step, the Afghan experience is being repeated in Chechnya,' said
Gen Lebed, commander of Russian forces in Moldova. 'We risk getting involved
in a war with the entire Moslem world.' He condemned the government for
sending 'untrained kids' into the region.
The criticism, when nine Russian soldiers have already died, highlights how
the Chechen crisis is dividing Russian leaders.
A strange alliance of liberal and communist politicians in the Russian
parliament yesterday opposed the action. The Duma, lower house, passed a
resolution describing the government's actions as 'unsatisfactory'.
But it urged President Boris Yeltsin to disarm the Chechens and to 'restore
legality' in the region, which declared its independence three years ago.
Russian forces, aiming to encircle Grozny, the Chechen capital, are being
impeded by swarms of civilians. The intervention appears to have dissolved
internal political disputes in Chechnya, and other peoples of the volatile
north Caucasus are rallying to aid their neighbours.
Negotiations between Chechen and Russian representatives in the North
Ossetian city of Vladikavkaz continued last night, but made no real
progress.
Itar-Tass news agency quoted Mr Oleg Soskovets, first deputy prime minister,
as saying Russia would give Rbs 1,000bn in aid to Chechnya once the conflict
ends.
It was possible yesterday to drive into Grozny in spite of Russian claims of
a blockade. The road from Nazran, capital of neighbouring Ingushetia, was
crowded with nervous Russian troops and littered with the remains of a dozen
burnt-out tanks and trucks.
Crossing into Chechnya, there were few visible defences - only a few
concrete blocks thrown across the road. Grizzled Chechen fighters carrying
Kalashnikov rifles and Molotov cocktails walked around.
At the village of Dovidenko, about 40km west of Grozny, several hundred
Chechen civilians swarmed towards a column of Russian troops and pleaded
with them to turn back.
One woman screamed, 'Do not make another Afghanistan]' Another shouted:
'This is not a battle against the Chechens it is war against the Moslems.'
A group of Chechen women was also sent to plead with the second Russian
column advancing from the republic of Dagestan. The third column of Russian
troops moved to within 5km of Grozny where reporters said they saw troops
blow up a car with a family inside fearing they were trying to destroy a
bridge.
West's fears rise, Page 2
</TEXT>
