<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / OFT calls for new rules on electrical goods warranties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS and NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading is to seek a new code of practice for the sale of
extended warranties on electrical products in a report out later this week.
The report is thought likely to attack the high-pressure sales tactics and
often misleading claims made by retailers when selling warranties, as well
as the lack of pricing information available for customers.
It will also call for measures to increase competition in the extended
warranties market.
For big electrical retailers such as Dixons and Comet, which make
significant profits from the sale of warranties - particularly before
Christmas - the timing of the report could hardly be worse.
However, the OFT has decided against an immediate referral of electrical
goods retailers to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission or a ban on
retailers' selling warranties at the point of sale. Both these measures
could be proposed in future by the OFT, should retailers fail to co-operate
with its other suggestions.
In spite of the recommendations, some consumer groups are likely to
criticise the OFT's failure to take tougher action. Some hoped retailers
would have had to provide details, at the point of sale, of the reliability
of their goods and of alternative warranty policies.
Extended warranties are insurance policies that provide extra protection
against product breakdown after the standard manufacturers' guarantees have
expired. They generally run for five years. Typical extended warranties cost
about Pounds 55 for five years' cover for a portable colour television to
Pounds 750 for a top-of-the-range personal computer.
City analysts have criticised electrical goods retailers for the amount of
profits warranties generate. Recent research by stockbrokers Collins Stewart
suggests that Dixons makes total gross profits of about Pounds 100m a year
from its extended warranties.
The OFT report is thought to include:
Action on transparency, with prices of warranties and servicing details to
be made readily available to customers in stores. Leaflets should be
available for shoppers to take away.
A long 'cooling off' period, during which customers can cancel their
warranty policies. For the first time, the OFT will publish free details of
reliability and repair costs for a wide range of electrical goods.
A new code of practice to oversee the sale of warranties in the UK.
However, high street retailers are likely to be pleased that several more
radical reforms have been rejected by the OFT. Those included forcing
retailers to disclose the commission they take on the sale of warranties.
Warranties may lose earning power, Page 7
</TEXT>
