<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: Stanhope
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is ironic that as city property prices start to rise, Stanhope, the part
owner of Broadgate, should be faced with the possibility of falling.
But its banks are running out of patience. Stanhope's assets match its
Pounds 148m of loans, following property revaluations, but it has no income
and carries Pounds 7m of overheads. It has had over a year to get
refinancing, but Mr Stuart Lipton, chairman and major shareholder, has
failed to capitalise on reviving confidence in property and cheap long-term
finance. Hence a last-minute scramble for survival ahead of Monday's
deadline.
The banks face a difficult choice. They can knock more than Pounds 30m off
the value of their debt, by selling to bidders British Land or PosTel, and
crystallise losses against a company with net value and an attractive asset.
Or they can opt for receivership, which would pare Stanhope's overheads and
facilitate the eventual sale of Broadgate, co-owned by Rosehaugh's
receivers. Those banks which wanted out could sell their debt. The downside
is that receivership can damage asset values, and would add to the banks'
reputation of taking receivership as the easy option.
There is an alternative. Roll over the debt, get equity funding to cover
administrative costs, and wait for Broadgate values to rise. The trouble is
that the main proponent of this is Mr Lipton, whose credibility has suffered
from an inability to turn ideas into reality. Given the harsh alternative of
receivership, it is not surprising the banks are pausing for thought.
</TEXT>
