<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: European telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The protagonists in the future European telecoms war are taking up
positions. Yesterday's joint venture between AT&amp;T and Unisource is the
latest move. As a sign of their seriousness, the partners have earmarked
roughly Dollars 1bn for investment over the next few years. Though the
venture's initial focus will be on supplying multinationals, it will be
positioned to serve the European long-distance market when that is opened to
competition in 1998. The same is true of BT's venture with MCI and France
Telecom's alliance with Deutsche Telekom. With margins on long-distance
calls high throughout much of Europe, a price war is only a matter of time.
BT looks set to adopt an aggressive strategy. It has relatively little to
lose from rivals invading its turf, since it already faces competition, and
much to win from poaching business from continental groups. By contrast, the
continental operators may play it defensively, seeking to protect their
patches. But such strategies are unlikely to pay off in the long run.
</TEXT>
