<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Chechen warning exposes rift in Russian military
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LEVINE and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GROZNY, VLADIKAVKAZ
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A rift among Russian top brass emerged yesterday as senior military
officials criticised the government's effort to subdue the breakaway Chechen
republic.
General Alexander Lebed and General Boris Gromov, who commanded Soviet
forces during the Afghan war, warned that the intervention in Chechnya could
lead to a bloody and drawn-out guerrilla war.
'Step by step, the Afghan experience is being repeated in Chechnya,' said
Gen Lebed, commander of Russian forces in Moldova. 'We risk getting involved
in a war with the entire Moslem world. Individual guerrillas will
indefinitely shoot at our tanks and kill our soldiers with single bullets.'
Gen Lebed condemned the government for sending 'untrained kids' into the
region and said their poor preparation was to blame for the immediate
surrender of 47 Russian troops to Chechen forces during the weekend.
The criticism, as nine Russian soldiers have already died, highlights how
deeply the Chechen crisis is dividing the Russian leadership.
A strange alliance of Russian liberal and communist politicians sharply
opposed the intervention in the Russian parliament yesterday. The Duma, or
lower house, passed an ambivalent resolution describing the government's
actions as 'unsatisfactory'.
But it urged President Boris Yeltsin to disarm the Chechens and to 'restore
legality' in the region which declared its independence from Russia three
years ago.
Only Mr Vladimir Zhirinovksy, the ultra-nationalist leader, gave his
unequivocal backing to the use of force.
Russian forces, aiming to encircle Grozny, the Chechen capital, are being
impeded by swarms of civilians. The slow-moving Russian intervention appears
to have dissolved internal political disputes in Chechnya, and other peoples
of the volatile North Caucasus are rallying to the defence of their
neighbours.
Negotiations between Chechen and Russian representatives in the North
Ossetian city of Vladikavkaz continued last night, but made no substantive
progress.
It was yesterday possible to drive into Grozny in spite of Russian claims to
have effectively blockaded the city. The road from neighbouring Ingushetia
was crowded with nervous Russian troops and littered with the burnt-out
remains of a dozen tanks and trucks.
Crossing into Chechnya, there were few visible defences  - only a few
concrete blocks thrown across the road. Grizzled Chechen fighters carrying
Kalashnikov rifles and Molotov cocktails walked around.
On the ground, Russian forces were slowed by encounters with the local
people and their supporters.
Mr Umar Gudaborshev, 31, a native Ingush, drove from his home in Kazakhstan
in central Asia to help. 'I am here to protect Chechnya. It is my homeland,'
he said.
West's fears, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
