<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Observer: Good relations
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Trivial pursuit. What has Procter &amp; Gamble, the US soap sud giant, in common
with Albright &amp; Wilson, the UK chemicals firm, soon to be refloated on the
UK stock market?
Answer: Both companies were started by brothers-in-law. William Procter and
James Gamble got together in Cincinnati, Ohio, in 1837 at the prompting of
their father-in-law. Arthur Albright got his big break in 1851, five years
after he married the local squire's daughter. He was on the lookout for a
chief engineer for his West Midlands phosphorus business and a husband for
his sister-in-law. John Edward Wilson came up trumps on both counts.
</TEXT>
