<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The series on Hollywood wives exerted a horrible sort of fascination. Living
Barbie-dolls, plasticly gorgeous or surgically bedizened, spokespersons for
the aesthetics of plush suburbia writ large, the intellect of airport
bookstall paperbacks writ small, and the morality of the second-hand car (or
husband or wife) salesman. There was a certain fun to be had from the
assembled kitsch, a horrified thrill in the realisation that virtual reality
had already arrived and, as in some sci-fi shocker, had taken over the real
people. They made the Stepford Wives seem normal.
Hollywood Kids (9pm, ITV) is as fascinating but much sadder. One
automatically bristles against the plaint of the poor little rich kid, but
some of these children, offspring of the famous, were genuinely hurt and
bewildered. Clark Gable's secret daughter had to have those tell-tale ears
altered. Having Judy Garland as a mom was no rainbow's end (nor was calling
Liza Minelli Sis). Next week the four-part series moves on to children who
were stars themselves.
</TEXT>
