<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Rail bidders face stringent controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Far-reaching controls on fares, timetables and levels of overcrowding will
have to be accepted by the bidders for the first eight train operating
companies due to be offered for sale today.
Fare increases will be limited on many commuter routes while rules designed
to prevent any increase in present levels of overcrowding have been drawn
up.
Mr Roger Salmon, franchising director responsible for the passenger train
operations sell-off, hopes to revive the momentum of British Rail
privatisation when he announces the terms for the first round of franchises.
But the 'passenger service requirements' are expected to provoke a political
storm, with critics of privatisation arguing that they will lead to a
reduction in services.
The service requirements will cover:
Timetables. Operators will be told the minimum number of trains which they
will be expected to run on weekdays and at weekends, the intervals between
trains, and the times of the first and last services.
Mr Salmon is expected to guarantee only an hourly service on some main lines
compared with current half-hourly services. Subsidies will be available for
these services but Mr Salmon expects additional trains to run to maximise
revenue and to compete effectively.
Fares. The franchising director is expected to intervene to hold down fares
on routes where rail travellers do not have a realistic alternative,
including rush-hour London routes and Edinburgh services. Responsibility for
fares in other large urban centres lies with local passenger transport
authorities.
Overcrowding. Train operators will be limited in terms of the numbers of
passengers they may carry. That is intended to ensure that if an operator
reduces services when demand falls, it will be obliged to increase services
when demand picks up. That measure is designed to prevent further
overcrowding.
At present train operators may carry up to 35 per cent more passengers than
they have seats.
Tickets. Train operators will be obliged to accept discount and full-fare
tickets sold by other train companies (though Apex fares, which have to be
bought in advance, will not be covered).
However, requiring operators to accept other companies' tickets could be
seen by critics as stifling price competition.
Consequently, while the lead operator on a particular route must accept
other companies' tickets, an operator offering an alternative service would
be allowed to provide a lower-priced ticket.
The rail regulator is considering proposals to concentrate the sale of
long-distance tickets on a limited number - perhaps 400 - stations.
Tickets are increasingly expected to be sold by tele-sales offices and
off-station outlets. However, rail user groups are concerned that this would
complicate ticket purchases.
Details of the franchises to be put up for sale in the first round will be
published today as pre-qualification documents.
Bidders will be expected to register an interest by March. Detailed bids
will then be invited in April, and the first sale is expected by December
next year.
</TEXT>
