<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Court ban on naming of lottery winner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Camelot, the National Lottery operator, was last night granted a High Court
injunction preventing Mirror Group or News International from naming the
winner of last Saturday's Pounds 17.9m lottery jackpot.
The legal action was taken after both the Daily Mirror and The Sun had
almost certainly discovered the identity the winner of the largest amount
ever won in the UK.
The winner, a factory worker in the north of England with three children,
had opted for anonymity as is his right under the rules of the National
Lottery.
The newspapers said last night that they had not been intending to publish
the winner's identity in today's newspapers but that they intended to
challenge the ex parte injunction, which remains in force until next
Tuesday, at the earliest possible opportunity.
Under the rules set by the National Lottery office the privacy of winners
receives strong protection if that is what they want. Unlike football pools
winners, who have to opt for privacy, National Lottery winners have an
automatic right of privacy until they opt for publicity in front of a
witness.
The excitement over last Saturday's jackpot, and the near inevitability of
the winner's identity becoming common knowledge, raises questions about how
practical the privacy rule will turn out to be. In many US lotteries winners
are not allowed to remain secret to ensure fair play.
On Monday, when a number of newspapers offered rewards for finding the
multi-million winner, Mr Ian Sproat, the National Heritage minister,
suggested that complaints about unfair behaviour by newspapers could go to
the Press Complaints Commission.
On Monday night The Sun and the Daily Mirror withdrew rewards of Pounds
10,000 and Pounds 5,000 respectively for identifying the winner. Though it
is very unlikely a newspaper will name the jackpot winner while the
injunction is in place, more and more details of the lifestyle and character
of the person are likely to emerge.
</TEXT>
