<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Regulator says auditors should have more freedom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Auditors should use their judgment in checking financial links between a
company and related parties, and not rely on following a set procedure, the
audit regulator said yesterday.
Draft proposals from the Auditing Practices Board mark a significant shift
away from rigid procedures designed to monitor companies, towards an
approach based on an auditor's experience and skills.
The regulator's recommendation follows strict proposals put forward in March
by the Accounting Standards Board to combat fraud. Several corporate
failures have been found to stem from undisclosed links with related
parties.
The standards board has proposed far-reaching requirements for directors to
disclose related-party transactions which go beyond those listed in
companies legislation.
Related parties would include individuals or companies connected with,
influenced by, or controlled by the company, its pension funds, its
directors, and managers, and their immediate families.
Mr David Lindsell, chairman of the practices board's working party, said
that checking disclosures on related party links in a large company would
lead to a 'huge' increase in audit costs.
He added that the thrust of the proposals did not concern the detection of
fraud, as most companies entered into only legitimate transactions with
related parties. Auditors had to use their judgment in checking the
disclosures and identifying inherent internal risks.
'However,' said Mr Lindsell, 'if the auditor assesses the risk of
undisclosed transactions as high, the proposal provides guidance as to the
procedures that could be followed.'
The practices board hopes that its draft proposal will become a standard,
with the force of law.
</TEXT>
