<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Construction industry suffers big fall in orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBYN CHALMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prospects for a significant improvement in demand for construction work this
year are waning as official statistics released today show building activity
tapering off.
Department of the Environment figures indicate that activity in the public
sector plummeted in the third quarter, with the housing and infrastructure
sectors showing big falls in orders compared with last year. Contractors
believe this signals an end to the upward trend in order levels seen in the
past year.
The future does not look much brighter. Mr Christopher Vickers, construction
spokesman for the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, said cuts in the
roads programme and the chancellor's over-reliance on the private finance
initiative would do little to maintain workload levels in the public sector
next year.
Statistics showed that, at constant 1990 prices, public housing and housing
association orders in the third quarter were 24 per cent lower than in the
previous three months and 36 per cent lower than in the comparable period
last year.
Infrastructure orders fell 33 per cent compared with the previous three
months and 39 per cent compared with the corresponding period last year.
This was offset by a steady rise in orders for new work in the private
commercial and industrial sectors. The total volume of new orders was 1 per
cent higher than the previous three months but 1 per cent lower than a year
ago.
The slowdown in orders has not yet filtered through to building material
producers, and figures released yesterday by the institution show that
building prices were 11 per cent higher than a year ago.
The organisation estimated that building prices across the country rose 3.4
per cent in the three months to the end of September. Prices were expected
to rise 5.6 per cent in the next 12 months and 4.5 per cent the following
year.
Mr Vickers said tender prices had reacted to the rising costs of site
labour, materials and sub-contractors. He thought that in the short term
increases in input costs, particularly labour, would fuel further prices
rises.
Mr Vickers believed, however, that by the end of the year the situation
would change and there would be an easing of tender price inflation.
</TEXT>
