<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Contractors to manage Scottish roads
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Office plans to put the management of Scotland's motorways and
main dual carriageways into the hands of private contractors by early 1996,
in what it sees as a big step towards a private-sector road management
industry.
Three groups of roads are likely to be offered under five-year contracts
each likely to be worth Pounds 25m to Pounds 35m.
The remaining 70 per cent of Scotland's trunk road network is to be divided
into five geographical units. A managing agent will be appointed for each
unit to co-ordinate the work of local councils for routine and winter
maintenance.
The managing agent might be a private company or a lead local authority
appointed by the councils. The arrangement would be reviewed after three
years. Roads would be managed under contracts agreed with the Scottish
Office and monitored by an audit unit.
The new arrangements have to come into effect by April 1 1996, when the nine
regional councils which maintain trunk roads and motorways on behalf of the
Scottish Office are abolished and replaced by 28 single-tier councils.
The government believes that the new councils will be too small to manage
parts of the trunk road network and is taking the opportunity to involve the
private sector in road management  - an element in the government's private
finance initiative.
In England local government reform is less advanced and only four roads have
been proposed for contracts that include designing, building and financing
them.
The new arrangements, set out in a consultation document, do not cover the
southern stretches of the M74 motorway. Here the Scottish Office hopes to
reach agreement with a consortium which would design, build, finance and
operate the remaining stretches of the motorway and manage 100km of road
between Carlisle and Abington, Lanarkshire, for 15 to 20 years.
Future Management and Maintenance of Scotland's Trunk Road Network. Scottish
Office Industry Department, New St Andrew's House, Edinburgh EH1 3TG.
</TEXT>
