<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Ofwat critical of bigger suppliers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three of the 10 big water and sewerage companies fell short of the level of
service customers could reasonably expect in at least one of seven areas
measured by Ofwat, the industry regulator said yesterday.
Of the three  - Anglian, Thames and Yorkshire  - Thames's performance was
the poorest, scoring 'good' marks in only one area of service where the
companies were directly comparable and 'below' or 'well below' average in
the other three.
Ofwat's findings are likely to stoke criticism of the big water and sewerage
concerns, privatised in 1989. Virtually all have since been pilloried for
their high profits and the big salary increases awarded to senior
executives.
Ofwat said smaller water companies, particularly those concentrating on
drinking water, had the highest standards of service in 1993-94.
The highest accolades went to South Staffordshire and York Waterworks, two
'water only' groups. Both performed particularly well in the four measures
of service where the companies were directly comparable.
Five companies  - Southern, Bristol, Hartlepool, Mid Southern, and Sutton
District, performed well. All except Southern are 'water only' concerns.
</TEXT>
