<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Thai confidence vote averted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Thailand's agriculture minister resigned yesterday, averting a no-confidence
motion that could have shaken the government days after defection of the New
Aspiration party in the ruling coalition. The opposition had planned to call
a no-confidence motion today against the minister, Mr Niphon Promphan, and
his former deputy, Mr Suthep Thueksuban, because of allegations that Mr
Suthep had manipulated a land reform programme to favour rich landowners. Mr
Niphon submitted his resignation to Mr Chuan Leekpai, prime minister, to
take responsibility for the scandal threatening to taint the government and
Mr Chuan's Democrat party. Mr Niphon and Mr Suthep, members of the Democrat
party, insist they are innocent. Mr Suthep resigned as deputy agriculture
minister last week, saying it would allow him to defend his actions without
being accused of trying to cling to his position.
</TEXT>
