<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 94 / Retailers find little cheer at Christmas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Retailers seem set for a gloomy Christmas. With 11 trading days left, a
business survey yesterday reported retailers' confidence falling and
suggested that profit margins will be under severe pressure.
The survey, from the Confederation of British Industry, provides fresh
evidence of the 'feel bad' factor souring Britain's economic recovery.
Weak sales forced the retail trade to keep annual price increases in
November at their lowest level for at least 11 years, the CBI said.
Mr James May, director general of the British Retail Consortium, said
retailers were likely to see a 'tough Christmas'. Official retail sales
data, due tomorrow, were likely to show High Street inflation was lower than
1 per cent in November, he said.
The CBI survey is expected to fuel stock market concerns that intense price
competition and low consumer spending will further erode profits and margins
in the run-up to Christmas.
However, it boosted City hopes that November's official inflation data,
published today, will show continuing low price pressures. This might ease
some of the impetus for another interest rates rise, fuelled earlier this
week by rising raw material costs.
Yesterday's data indicate why some shops have introduced pre-Christmas
sales. 'In terms of margins and profits it is very tough - people are going
to have to adjust their ideas of profits,' Mr May said.
The CBI said its survey showed retailers reporting the lowest annual growth
in selling prices in November since the price survey started in 1983.
Selling prices were reduced by 24 per cent of shops compared with last
November. Some 25 per cent of shops expected prices to be lower in December
than last Christmas, with 37 per cent expecting them to be higher, a
positive balance of 12.
Discounting in November succeeded in slightly boosting overall retail sales
volumes, the survey suggested. The level of sales reported by retailers in
November was slightly better than in October, with 40 per cent of retailers
reporting sales higher than in the previous November.
However, this was below retailers' expectations in the previous quarterly
survey, and the level of optimism fell to its lowest level for two years,
with 74 per cent of retailers expecting no improvements in the next three
months.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, chairman of the CBI's survey panel, said there appeared
to be a slowdown in sales growth, partly as a result of recent tax and
interest rate rises. But consumers may be leaving shopping until the end of
the Christmas period, he said.
</TEXT>
